      <div class="problem-block">
        <h3 id="problem-title" style="margin-bottom:8px">A question</h3>
        <p id="problem-text" style="line-height:1.7">What happens when performance leaves the theatre and enters the phone?

When movement is experienced through a screen? When social media becomes one of the main places where people see, present and construct themselves?

These are no longer questions only for artists.

They concern anyone living in the age of cameras and content.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WHY -->
      <div class="what-block">
        <h3 id="why-title">Why we are doing this</h3>
        <p id="why-p1" style="margin-bottom:16px">We live in the age of content. Every day we film stories, Reels, videos, calls. The camera is now part of our lives — whether we like it or not.</p>
        <p id="why-p2" style="margin-bottom:16px">We're constantly taught algorithms, reach and attention metrics. But almost nobody talks about the person on the other side of the camera.</p>
        <p id="why-p3">Why are you one person in life and another on camera? Why does your body tense up? Why does presence disappear?</p>
      </div>

      <!-- RESEARCH -->
      <div class="what-block">
        <h3 id="research-title">What we will explore</h3>
        <ul id="research-list" style="list-style:none;padding:0">
          <li id="research-1" style="padding:6px 0;font-size:15px">The phone as a new stage</li>
          <li id="research-2" style="padding:6px 0;font-size:15px">Performance in the age of social media</li>
          <li id="research-3" style="padding:6px 0;font-size:15px">Presence and the body in the frame</li>
          <li id="research-4" style="padding:6px 0;font-size:15px">The camera as a space for expression</li>
          <li id="research-5" style="padding:6px 0;font-size:15px">How movement changes through the screen</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

